# Testing

## Expected errors must stay off the console

Passing tests must not print expected failures to the terminal. When code under test throws, rejects, or otherwise reports an expected error via **stderr** or **`console.error`**, suppress or capture that output for the duration of the test.

Use helpers from [`src/test/suppress-expected-error-output.ts`](src/test/suppress-expected-error-output.ts):

- **`withSuppressedErrorOutput`** — discard stderr / `console.error` while running the callback (sync or async).
- **`withCapturedErrorOutput`** — capture stderr / `console.error` when the test must assert on warning or error text.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — expected CLI failure, no console noise
await withSuppressedErrorOutput(async () =>
{
    await runProgram(['node', 'parser-lr', 'table', 'generate', '-g', missingPath]);
    expect(process.exitCode).toBe(1);
});

// ✅ GOOD — expected warnings still asserted, not printed
const { output } = await withCapturedErrorOutput(async () =>
{
    await createProgram().parseAsync([/* table generate … */]);
});
expect(output).toContain('shift/reduce conflict');

// ❌ BAD — passing test leaves ENOENT / formatUserError on stderr
await runProgram(['node', 'parser-lr', 'table', 'generate', '-g', missingPath]);
expect(process.exitCode).toBe(1);
```

Wrap **`expect(() => …).toThrow(…)`** in `withSuppressedErrorOutput` when the callee may log before throwing (CLI, `runProgram`, similar error formatters).

Conflict **warnings** that are part of a successful build are not exceptions; capture them with **`withCapturedErrorOutput`** when asserting on the text.

Do not globally disable Jest console reporting; scope suppression to the test or block that expects the error.
